She got in.                     

02:21.007 --> 02:23.075
            Oh, I sense the mood
                     of the bar.

02:23.143 --> 02:25.277
    You're all suffering from   
            the winter blues,   

02:25.345 --> 02:26.845
the shortened                   
daylight hours,                 

02:26.913 --> 02:29.648
the cold numbing weather,       
 the bleak sense of isolation.  

02:29.716 --> 02:31.684
It's what we in the psychiatric 
        profession call,        

02:31.751 --> 02:33.118
          the jackpot!          

02:34.854 --> 02:36.522
    Frasier and I have          
        a wonderful plan        

02:36.589 --> 02:37.856
to lift our spirits.            

02:37.924 --> 02:39.892
  What, are you gonna buy some  
     toys and canned goods      

02:39.993 --> 02:41.593
        and hand 'em out        
    to underprivileged kids?    

02:41.661 --> 02:43.595
                    Well, no.   

02:43.663 --> 02:46.231
             We're checking into
              a luxury hotel for
              a getaway weekend,

02:46.299 --> 02:47.666
             just the two of us.

02:47.734 --> 02:48.901
                     Oh.        

02:48.968 --> 02:51.236
    Well, that'll make          
      some bellboys happy.      

02:52.939 --> 02:55.007
      So, aren't you gonna      
         bring the kid?         

02:55.075 --> 02:57.276
  Well, we would, but we find   
  that we make better parents   

02:57.344 --> 02:58.711
    if we occasionally          
          take a break          

02:58.778 --> 03:00.679
    from our parenting          
    responsibilities.           

03:00.747 --> 03:03.015
      Hey, you don't have       
      to justify it to me.      

03:03.083 --> 03:05.017
  You know, my parents ran off  
        for a year              

03:05.085 --> 03:07.019
 with the Pentecostal caravan.  

03:07.087 --> 03:08.854
                    Oh, sure,   

03:08.922 --> 03:11.890
they called once in a while, but
 they were speaking in tongues. 

03:11.958 --> 03:13.492
                        Yeah.   

03:13.560 --> 03:16.495
      It was just by chance that
          they came back at all.

03:18.531 --> 03:20.199
              Sam!              

03:20.266 --> 03:21.467
What are you doing?!            

03:21.534 --> 03:22.568
          I'm working.          

03:22.669 --> 03:24.003
     What does it look like     
        I'm doing?              

03:24.070 --> 03:26.005
Well, excuse me,                
but this is the 12th!           

03:26.072 --> 03:27.973
              Yeah. Well, I work
                    on the 12th.

03:28.041 --> 03:30.142
  Well I ovulate on the 12th!   

03:32.245 --> 03:34.513
              How was I supposed
                to know that?   

03:34.581 --> 03:35.481
                 We all knew it.

03:35.548 --> 03:37.216
                     It's in the
                     newsletter.

03:37.283 --> 03:39.818
Sam, just finish up             
whatever you're doing,          

03:39.886 --> 03:41.153
and let's                       
get pregnant.                   

03:41.221 --> 03:43.155
    Boy, that's what I like     
         about Rebecca.         

03:43.223 --> 03:45.557
  She's just an old-fashioned   
        girl, isn't she?        
                            Mmm.

03:45.625 --> 03:47.526
You cannot order me             
to perform!                     

03:47.594 --> 03:49.895
I don't want to have sex        
with you, okay? No sex.         

03:49.963 --> 03:51.864
Who said that?                  

03:51.931 --> 03:53.565
        I don't believe this.   

03:53.633 --> 03:55.534
If we don't do it now we have   
          to wait a whole month!

03:55.602 --> 03:57.069
      I'm not in the mood,      
        all right?              

03:57.137 --> 03:58.971
Who's saying                    
these things?                   

03:59.039 --> 04:01.006
              Sam, what is wrong
                    with you?   

04:01.074 --> 04:02.041
I don't know.                   

04:02.108 --> 04:03.509
 Boy, you two sure argue a lot  

04:03.576 --> 04:04.777
              for two people who
                  aren't in love

04:04.844 --> 04:06.445
                but want to have
                         a baby.

04:06.513 --> 04:08.213
  I mean, I don't know, maybe   
  that's normal for two people  

04:08.281 --> 04:09.882
    who aren't in love          
    but want to have a baby.    

04:11.317 --> 04:12.584
        I wouldn't know.        
    I've never known anyone     

04:12.652 --> 04:14.253
    who wasn't in love          
but wanted to have a baby.      

04:14.320 --> 04:15.587
        Woody, shut up!         

04:15.655 --> 04:18.589
        Hey, don't get me caught
            in your sick web.   

04:20.660 --> 04:23.595
Come here, come here, hey,      
just-just relax.                

04:23.663 --> 04:25.064
            Remember            
     what the doctor said?      

04:25.131 --> 04:27.232
You know, how stress can        
keep you from conceiving.       

04:27.300 --> 04:29.568
Well, all-all we do             
nowadays is fight.              

04:29.636 --> 04:30.469
          Oh, shut up!          
No, you shut up!                

04:30.537 --> 04:31.603
                No, you shut up!
You shut up!                    

04:31.671 --> 04:33.605
Shut me up!                     
                     (shouting):
                        Shut up!

04:36.509 --> 04:37.543
     This is what               
     I'm talking about.         

04:37.610 --> 04:38.711
        This is stress.         

04:38.778 --> 04:40.279
        Oh, yeah?               
  Well, you've got ten minutes  

04:40.347 --> 04:42.281
  to get yourself together and  
 get your bad attitude in order 

04:42.349 --> 04:43.749
    and get over to my place    

04:43.817 --> 04:46.285
  and we're gonna make a cute   
          little baby!          

04:46.353 --> 04:48.253
          I hate her.           

04:49.823 --> 04:51.757
         Now, at 2:00,          
        we have a choice        

04:51.825 --> 04:53.759
      between a sumptuous       
            high tea            

04:53.827 --> 04:56.028
         and a relaxing         
        Swedish massage.        

04:56.096 --> 04:57.329
    Ah, 2:00.                   

04:57.397 --> 04:58.931
Right about then I'll be jumping
into my mail truck,             

04:58.998 --> 05:00.099
ripping off my shoes            

05:00.166 --> 05:01.767
and trying to save my toes      
from frostbite.                 

05:01.835 --> 05:03.769
              Hey, nobody held a
                gun to your head

05:03.837 --> 05:06.338
                and said, "Be   
                     a mailman."

05:06.406 --> 05:08.474
  Frasier, we have a problem.   

05:08.541 --> 05:09.842
            I've just gotten off

05:09.909 --> 05:11.377
        the phone               
with Frederick's teacher,       

05:11.444 --> 05:13.379
         who informs me         
  that your son has come down   

05:13.446 --> 05:14.780
  with a case of chicken pox.   

05:14.848 --> 05:17.116
     No! I'm not giving up      
        my nonrefundable        

05:17.183 --> 05:18.751
        getaway weekend!        

05:18.818 --> 05:20.419
                Frasier, your   
                child is ill.   

05:20.487 --> 05:22.421
    (sighing)                   

05:22.489 --> 05:24.556
Oh, you're right,               
of course you're right.         

05:24.624 --> 05:25.991
I'm-I'm ashamed.                

05:26.059 --> 05:26.992
              And deservedly so.

05:27.060 --> 05:28.961
                 Shall we?      

05:29.029 --> 05:30.963
         I'm on my way.         

05:31.031 --> 05:32.965
         Well, friends,         
I've discovered a new way       

05:33.033 --> 05:34.967
of getting over the winter      
             blues.             

05:35.035 --> 05:37.302
      Instead of enjoying       
        a luxury weekend        

05:37.370 --> 05:39.338
         being coddled          
     in a four-star hotel,      

05:39.406 --> 05:40.539
I'll be bathing                 
an itchy,                       

05:40.607 --> 05:43.575
whiney two-year old             
in oatmeal.                     

05:43.643 --> 05:44.877
                  Say, Fras, uh,
                    you know,   

05:44.944 --> 05:46.745
     if you have trouble getting
        rid of that reservation,

05:46.813 --> 05:49.348
     I sure know a couple who've
      been under a lot of stress

05:49.416 --> 05:50.616
                  and fighting a
                     lot lately,

05:50.684 --> 05:52.351
    and, you know, they could   
                 benefit from a,

05:52.419 --> 05:54.186
                  a nice weekend
                     in a hotel.

05:54.254 --> 05:56.321
Thanks for thinking             
of us, Sammy.                   
                         Yeah.  

05:57.557 --> 05:59.124
              Listen, uh, I just
                 got to run home

05:59.192 --> 06:00.325
            and get my travel   
                iron real quick.

06:00.393 --> 06:01.593
I'm not talking about you guys. 

06:01.661 --> 06:02.594
      I'm talking about me      
          and Rebecca.          

06:02.662 --> 06:03.629
Yeah, stupid.                   

06:03.697 --> 06:04.863
You should have                 
thought of that.                

06:04.931 --> 06:06.632
            You made the same   
                mistake, pal.   

06:06.700 --> 06:08.667
Boy, we-we                      

06:08.735 --> 06:10.602
really could have used          
that weekend.                   

06:12.005 --> 06:13.605
Come on,                        
what do you say, huh?           

06:13.673 --> 06:15.274
     Please?                    

06:15.342 --> 06:16.475
                  Oh, all right.

06:16.543 --> 06:18.510
            Here, take the room.

06:18.578 --> 06:19.945
            Conceive your child.

06:20.013 --> 06:21.447
                        Go make.

06:21.514 --> 06:24.616
             Well, yeah, doesn't
                it at least make
                 you feel better

06:24.684 --> 06:26.318
              knowing somebody's
                     having fun?

06:26.386 --> 06:27.686
              No.               

06:29.089 --> 06:31.190
    I know it sounds petty,     
         but frankly I,         

06:31.257 --> 06:33.692
I can't think of anything       
 that would make me feel worse. 

06:33.760 --> 06:36.362
    Uh, Frasier, dear,          

06:36.429 --> 06:38.030
I can't remember.               

06:38.098 --> 06:39.865
Have you ever had               
the chicken pox?                

06:39.933 --> 06:41.166
FRASIER:                        
Oh!                             

06:41.234 --> 06:43.502
I can always think of something 

06:43.570 --> 06:45.504
that would make him feel worse. 

06:52.912 --> 06:54.480
        Hey, everybody.         

06:55.815 --> 06:57.649
      Woody, uh, set me up      
     with a beer, will you?     

06:57.717 --> 06:59.852
 Well, aren't you gonna finish  
  your mail route, Mr. Clavin?  

06:59.919 --> 07:01.186
        Are you kidding?        

07:01.254 --> 07:02.921
     There's too much snow      
      and sleet out there.      

07:05.792 --> 07:07.993
            Besides it's getting
                  a little dark.

07:09.396 --> 07:10.829
I don't blame you,              
Cliff,                          

07:10.897 --> 07:12.231
I hate going out                
in this weather.                

07:12.298 --> 07:14.566
Hmm. Yeah, you guys are a bunch 
          of whining,           

07:14.634 --> 07:16.235
      complaining weenies.      

07:16.302 --> 07:18.504
         What, you like         
         this weather?          

07:18.571 --> 07:20.506
     Oh, is that the topic?     

07:21.808 --> 07:23.642
  Well, are we gonna let this   
    weather defeat us?          

07:23.710 --> 07:25.244
  Or are we gonna fight back?   

07:25.311 --> 07:26.345
Hey, I'm with you, Doc.         

07:26.413 --> 07:27.780
So what shall we do?            

07:27.847 --> 07:29.148
Hey, you guys                   
ever hear                       

07:29.215 --> 07:30.916
of something called             
the Polar Bear Club?            

07:30.984 --> 07:32.084
        Uh...                   

07:32.152 --> 07:33.452
                        PAUL:   
            Well, it's great.   

07:33.520 --> 07:35.154
 We used to do it all the time  
        where I grew up.        

07:35.221 --> 07:36.588
Bunch of guys get in their cars.

07:36.656 --> 07:37.823
 They drive down to the ocean.  

07:37.891 --> 07:38.957
        They strip down         
    to their skivvies           

07:39.025 --> 07:40.259
    and they run right          
        into the water.         

07:40.326 --> 07:44.196
Uh, I was thinking more         
of a, uh, belching contest.     

07:45.832 --> 07:47.666
        Oh, I don't know, uh,   
             loudest or longest?

07:47.734 --> 07:49.568
PAUL:                           
Fine. Fine,                     

07:49.636 --> 07:51.003
    but you guys don't know     
      what you're missing.      

07:51.071 --> 07:53.205
     Now, when we were kids     
we didn't care if it was January

07:53.273 --> 07:55.274
  or February, we just jumped   
    in that ocean and swam.     

07:55.342 --> 07:56.642
                  It felt great.

07:56.710 --> 07:58.610
It was like we scored one       
against winter.                 

07:58.678 --> 08:00.612
    Hey, if it's good enough    
    for Mr. Krapence.           

08:00.680 --> 08:02.214
  Well, are we up to it, men?   

08:02.282 --> 08:03.916
                      All right.
Well, uh, well,                 
it's one of the earthly thrills 

08:03.983 --> 08:05.884
I haven't tried yet.            
                    Let's do it!

08:05.952 --> 08:08.954
        GUYS (chanting):        
    Polar Bear! Polar Bear!     

08:09.022 --> 08:11.357
    Polar Bear! Polar Bear!     

08:11.424 --> 08:13.959
    Polar Bear! Polar Bear!     

08:14.027 --> 08:15.294
Polar Bear...                   

08:15.362 --> 08:17.463
So, Paul, where were you        
brought up?                     

08:17.530 --> 08:19.298
                    Honolulu.   

08:29.843 --> 08:31.477
             Whoa!              

08:31.544 --> 08:34.246
          Three bucks           
    for a lousy pack of gum.    

08:34.313 --> 08:36.914
                        REBECCA:
              Sam, get away from
                  the honor bar.

08:36.982 --> 08:38.250
        Honor bar.              

08:38.318 --> 08:40.251
              Oh.               

08:47.727 --> 08:49.695
        Hey, sweetheart,        
    what do you think?          

08:50.764 --> 08:53.966
 If it's a boy, we name it Sam? 

08:54.034 --> 08:56.001
            Oh, I don't know.   

08:56.069 --> 08:57.536
                     You know, I
                  always thought

08:57.604 --> 08:59.171
          that naming your child
         after yourself was like

08:59.239 --> 09:02.007
     saying you want him to grow
         up to be just like you,

09:02.075 --> 09:03.676
              to like the things
                    you like,   

09:03.743 --> 09:05.544
                  to act the way
                         you do.

09:05.612 --> 09:07.513
        Okay, Sam it is.        

09:10.016 --> 09:11.950
             Yeah.              

09:12.018 --> 09:13.952
              Sam.              

09:15.355 --> 09:17.122
You know something,             
Dad?                            

09:17.190 --> 09:19.291
I really like my name.          

09:19.359 --> 09:21.527
                    Thanks, Sam.

09:21.594 --> 09:23.195
  Beautiful evening, isn't it?  

09:23.263 --> 09:24.963
    Oh, sure is, Dad.           

09:25.031 --> 09:27.132
  Say, how's that paper route   
            coming?             

09:27.200 --> 09:28.634
Just fine, Dad.                 

09:28.702 --> 09:30.302
Before long,                    
I'll have enough saved up       

09:30.370 --> 09:31.570
to buy that                     
baseball glove.                 

09:31.638 --> 09:32.871
              Ah!               

09:32.939 --> 09:34.006
 Tell me again what it was like 

09:34.074 --> 09:35.507
         when you were          
in the major leagues, Dad.      

09:35.575 --> 09:38.577
Oh, come on, you must be getting
     tired of hearing that.     

09:38.645 --> 09:40.012
How could I ever                
get tired                       

09:40.080 --> 09:42.014
of hearing                      
about you, Dad?                 

09:42.082 --> 09:44.750
        (knock at door)         

09:46.553 --> 09:48.487
          I'm coming.           

09:48.555 --> 09:49.655
             Whoa.              

09:49.723 --> 09:51.557
         Hope it's not          
     the honor bar police.      

09:53.126 --> 09:54.259
                    Oh!         

09:54.327 --> 09:55.728
          I'm sorry. Wrong room.

09:55.795 --> 09:57.529
          I went out to get some
             stuff for the kids,

09:57.597 --> 09:59.098
         and I guess I got lost.
        I'm sorry about that.   

09:59.165 --> 10:01.000
Oh, yeah, excuse me,            
if you don't mind me asking,    

10:01.067 --> 10:02.868
uh, how many kids               
you got?                        

10:02.936 --> 10:04.570
                     Three boys.
      Wow.                      

10:04.637 --> 10:05.738
Oh, that's great.               
                        Yeah.   

10:05.805 --> 10:06.739
How long have you               
been married?                   

10:06.806 --> 10:08.073
                    20 years.   

10:08.141 --> 10:09.174
    Wow.                        

10:09.242 --> 10:10.876
Hey, listen, uh,                

10:10.944 --> 10:12.878
you don't have any advice       
for a guy                       

10:12.946 --> 10:14.913
who's about to start            
his family, do you?             

10:14.981 --> 10:17.516
                 Well, you know,
                        it's,   

10:17.584 --> 10:19.518
         like it's no big secret
                what you need   

10:19.586 --> 10:20.786
                to start a happy
                         family.

10:20.854 --> 10:22.354
                      Love!     

10:22.422 --> 10:24.356
              You know, if a man
                and woman really

10:24.424 --> 10:27.026
      love each other, they pass
        that love onto the kids,

10:27.093 --> 10:29.294
             and they'll grow up
             strong and healthy.

10:29.362 --> 10:31.530
Yeah, well, I mean,             
I know love's okay              

10:31.598 --> 10:33.866
and everything,                 
but, uh, you know,              

10:33.933 --> 10:36.068
what about, uh,                 
those other important things    

10:36.136 --> 10:38.237
like friendship                 
and a sense of humor?           

10:38.304 --> 10:40.105
            A sense of humor?   

10:40.173 --> 10:41.473
    Yeah.                       

10:41.541 --> 10:42.908
            What's that gonna   
                        get you?

10:42.976 --> 10:45.310
                 I mean, look at
            Martin and Lewis.   

10:45.378 --> 10:46.645
                They had a sense
                    of humor.   

10:46.713 --> 10:47.780
            But were they happy?

10:47.847 --> 10:50.049
No, they weren't.               

10:50.116 --> 10:52.785
                  No, because it
                     takes love.

10:52.852 --> 10:54.319
You've got a lot                
of that, huh?                   

10:54.387 --> 10:56.221
                 Me? No, I can't
                stand my missus.

10:56.289 --> 10:58.557
        It's been 20 years of   
             living hell for me.

11:00.160 --> 11:02.461
              BOY:              
      Hey look, it's Dad.       

11:02.529 --> 11:03.829
    What's the matter?          

11:03.897 --> 11:05.898
  Can't you even find your way  
    back to the room,           

11:05.965 --> 11:07.166
    you stupid idiot.           

11:07.233 --> 11:09.201
             Those are the kids.

11:10.704 --> 11:12.271
             BOY 2:             
         Come on, Dad,          
    move your fat ass,          

11:12.339 --> 11:15.007
      and give me 50 bucks      
        for the arcade.         

11:15.075 --> 11:18.143
             On my good days, I,
             uh, pray for death.

